lects of Middle English and also into Anglo-Norman French. There are a number of places in England named with this word, as for example Lund in Lancashire, East Yorkshire, and North Yorkshire, Lunt in Merseyside, and Lound in Lincolnshire, Nottinghamshire, and Suffolk, and the surname may derive from any of these. As a Swedish surname it is probably most often ornamental.","German: habitational name from any of the places called Lund or Lunden in Schleswig-Holstein."],"variants":[{"name":"Lundt","meanings":["German: variant of   Lund  ."]},{"name":"Lunt","meanings":["English (northern): topographic name for someone who lived by a grove, from Old Norse <i>lundr</i> (see   Lund  )."]},{"name":"Lunn","meanings":["English, Norwegian, and Danish: variant of   Lund  ."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Emma de Lund was born about 1156, in Sessay, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Thomas Darell. She had at least 1 son with Robert FitzRobert or de Thweng."},"et":{"about 1156–":"umbes 1156–Surnud","1156–Female":"1156–Surnud","1145–1246":"1145–1246","1178–1234":"1178–1234","–Male":"Surnud","1246":"1246","1234":"1234","1178":"1178","1145":"1145","1156":"1156","about 1156":"umbes 1156","Durham, England, United Kingdom":"Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sessay, Yorkshire, England":"S